[
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm trying to understand why does Lean accept this proof term</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⊆</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∩</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⊆</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∩</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"n\">xs</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xu</span><span class=\"bp\">⟩</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↦</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xs</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xu</span><span class=\"bp\">⟩</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Whereas both of the following fail</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">},</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∈</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∈</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">},</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∈</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∩</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∈</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∩</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"n\">xs</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xu</span><span class=\"bp\">⟩</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↦</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xs</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xu</span><span class=\"bp\">⟩</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">-- type mismatch</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">--  fun x x_1 ↦ ?m.1714</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">-- has type</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">--   (x : x✝ ∈ s ∩ u) → (x_1 : ?m.1715 x) → ?m.1716 x x_1 : Sort (imax ?u.1709 ?u.1712)</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">-- but is expected to have type</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">--   x✝ ∈ s ∩ u → x✝ ∈ t ∩ u : Prop</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">-- the following variables have been introduced by the implicit lambda feature</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">--   x✝ : α</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">-- you can disable implicit lambdas using `@` or writing a lambda expression with `{}` or `[]` binder annotations.</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∈</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∈</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∈</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∩</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∈</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∩</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"n\">xs</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xu</span><span class=\"bp\">⟩</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↦</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xs</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xu</span><span class=\"bp\">⟩</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">-- Application type mismatch: In the application</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">--   h xs</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">-- the argument</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">--   xs</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">-- has type</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">--   x ∈ s : Prop</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">-- but is expected to have type</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">--   α : Type u_1</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I understand both of the errors: in the first case I should have written <code>fun {x} ...</code> and in the second <code> ⟨h x xs, xu⟩</code>. But then why is the first example correct? Shouldn't it be flagged with the same error as one of the failing examples?</p>\n<p>Btw, I took this example from course \"mathematics in lean\", <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathematics_in_lean/C04_Sets_and_Functions.html#sets\">chapter: Sets and Functions</a>.</p>",
        "id": 538191792,
        "sender_full_name": "Michał Pacholski",
        "timestamp": 1757328793
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Because <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Set.Subset#doc\">docs#Set.Subset</a> uses <code>⦃a⦄</code></p>",
        "id": 538193426,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1757329261
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's a binder between <code>{}</code> and <code>()</code></p>",
        "id": 538193539,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1757329292
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you had included variables and imports, I could have verified that worked</p>",
        "id": 538193650,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1757329323
    },
    {
        "content": "<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Tactic</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">variable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⊆</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∩</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⊆</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∩</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">unfold</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Subset</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">instHasSubset</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">at</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">unfold</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">LE</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">le</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">instLE</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Subset</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">at</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">dsimp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">only</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">at</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"c1\">-- h : ∀ ⦃a : ℕ⦄, a ∈ s → a ∈ t</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">exact</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"n\">xs</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xu</span><span class=\"bp\">⟩</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↦</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xs</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">xu</span><span class=\"bp\">⟩</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>It seems that <code>⊆</code> unfolds to <code>∀ ⦃a : ℕ⦄, a ∈ s → a ∈ t</code> rather than <code>∀ {a : ℕ}, a ∈ s → a ∈ t</code> which presumably explains the difference.</p>",
        "id": 538195396,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1757329841
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thank you! I didn't know about <code>⦃a⦄</code> binder. I'm also amazed with how helpful this community is: not only did I get the answer to my question, but I also learned how I could have found it out myself. I couldn't have asked for more.</p>",
        "id": 538211971,
        "sender_full_name": "Michał Pacholski",
        "timestamp": 1757334543
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"307953\">Ruben Van de Velde</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/Why.20fun.20x.20works.20for.20.E2.8A.86.20but.20not.20.E2.88.80.20.7Bx.7D/near/538193650\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If you had included variables and imports, I could have verified that worked</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I'll remember to do it next time!</p>",
        "id": 538212778,
        "sender_full_name": "Michał Pacholski",
        "timestamp": 1757334749
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>NB to see exactly what to unfold in the above, it's sometimes helpful to <code>set_option pp.notation false</code>. I didn't do this but only because I've been around long enough to know the names of the declarations underlying of a lot of the common notation.</p>",
        "id": 538213614,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1757334973
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For what it's worth, I used loogle to find where to look: <a href=\"https://loogle.lean-lang.org/?q=HasSubset+%28Set+_%29\">https://loogle.lean-lang.org/?q=HasSubset+%28Set+_%29</a></p>",
        "id": 538262692,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1757346674
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A helpful exploratory tactic, to deal with typeclass-defined notation, is <code>unfold_projs</code>:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Tactic</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">variable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⊆</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∩</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⊆</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∩</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">unfold_projs</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"c1\">-- ⊢ (s.inter u).Subset (t.inter u)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"c1\">-- Now we know it's `Set.Subset`.</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">unfold</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Subset</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"c1\">-- ⊢ ∀ ⦃a : ℕ⦄, a ∈ s.inter u → a ∈ t.inter u</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 538448977,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1757427355
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In the newest Lean version, if you right click on <code>⊆</code> and select \"go to definition\" in VS Code, it brings you to the HasSubset instance in Mathlib.Data.Set.Defs, and just a handful of lines before that you can see <code>Set.Subset</code>. There's still a little indirection here, but it's a lot nicer than a couple versions ago where it would only bring you to HasSubset itself.</p>",
        "id": 538449753,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1757427588
    }
]